WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.840
Hey, this is Rich.

00:00:00.860 --> 00:00:02.560
I'm the maintainer of the gt package.

00:00:02.640 --> 00:00:05.000
0.7 is out, so let's see what's actually in it.

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:11.160
Feature one, the new Word output table format for gt.

00:00:11.880 --> 00:00:16.320
With that, you could output a table to a Word document.

00:00:16.559 --> 00:00:19.360
And here's an example right here inside rstudio.

00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:21.480
I'm going to load up gt.

00:00:22.040 --> 00:00:23.920
I have this example table called Exhible.

00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:25.959
We can make a gt table out of that.

00:00:26.520 --> 00:00:30.520
And if you use gt save, we could output that to a Word document.

00:00:30.559 --> 00:00:33.799
We just have to use .docx in the file extension.

00:00:34.599 --> 00:00:38.759
Feature number two is a whole new class of vector formatting functions, and

00:00:38.759 --> 00:00:41.080
they can be used outside of gt proper.

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:44.720
All the work that was put into the column formatting functions, like

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:46.520
format number, format scientific.

00:00:47.119 --> 00:00:48.680
Now you get that outside of gt.

00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:52.200
Anywhere you want to use it, say for instance, inside of Cordo or

00:00:52.200 --> 00:00:54.000
R Markdown, inside a paragraph.

00:00:54.400 --> 00:00:58.919
You want to have some format numbers or our currency values, and I can have

00:00:58.919 --> 00:01:03.080
that without having to hack sign together with gt and its column formatters.

00:01:03.320 --> 00:01:06.040
So another new feature we have, this is feature number three, is

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:07.839
a new opt stylize function.

00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:13.239
With that, if you have a gt table and you don't want to style it with a lot

00:01:13.239 --> 00:01:18.720
of tab options or tab style statements, you can just use opt stylize.

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:22.559
You give it a style number, you give it a color, and gt just takes it away

00:01:22.919 --> 00:01:28.919
and stylizes your table with a nice set of colors and line styles for all

00:01:28.919 --> 00:01:30.000
the different parts of your table.

00:01:30.879 --> 00:01:31.879
And here's an example right here.

00:01:31.879 --> 00:01:35.760
My viewer, I just ran it over this code right here, which created a table

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:41.320
with all sorts of different locations, like summaries and footnotes and a header.

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:44.720
You can see right here, just by using stop stylize, we get a very nice

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:48.000
table as a result, and you can switch the color out if you really want to.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:51.559
Feature four is a new function called tab stub indent.

00:01:52.120 --> 00:01:55.400
What it allows you to do is to take row labels in the stub and indent them.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:59.400
Before you could not do that very easily by adding spaces or things like that.

00:01:59.919 --> 00:02:04.040
Very manual, not so easy, but with tab stub indent, you just give the rows

00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:06.480
you want to match and you just choose the indent level.

00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:08.360
You can also use increase or decrease here.

00:02:08.759 --> 00:02:09.679
It's really quite nice.

00:02:09.759 --> 00:02:13.279
And I'm just going to run this code and we see that the sizes here are

00:02:13.279 --> 00:02:16.559
indented by two tab stops, which is really nice.

00:02:16.559 --> 00:02:21.679
We selected all these with a match statement, and you can do all sorts of

00:02:21.679 --> 00:02:24.800
nice things with indentation, with tab stub indent.

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:29.039
So again, the feature five, we have a new function called format duration.

00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:32.440
It's a formatting function and it allows you to take any value.

00:02:32.479 --> 00:02:37.000
It can be numerical values or it can be diff time values and

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:38.720
format them as duration values.

00:02:39.119 --> 00:02:40.520
This is really quite neat.

00:02:40.520 --> 00:02:42.320
So I'm going to show you this in an example here.

00:02:42.679 --> 00:02:44.119
We have some SP 500 data.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.520
We're doing some stuff to it and a main thing we're doing in the time

00:02:48.520 --> 00:02:51.679
past column is running format duration.

00:02:51.919 --> 00:02:53.800
So let's actually see that in a table.

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:58.000
And we can see here that just with the default options or very default,

00:02:58.199 --> 00:03:00.679
defaulty options, we have the time past column.

00:03:01.199 --> 00:03:02.800
It's got number of days.

00:03:02.839 --> 00:03:06.279
It added the days to it, which is quite nice.

00:03:06.639 --> 00:03:08.320
And we can, you know, choose things.

00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:13.600
We can have things like narrow here and rerun the code and we get things like this.

00:03:13.600 --> 00:03:16.160
We have a narrow days designation.

00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:20.520
So if you have complex times going in the past, this will also work.

00:03:20.559 --> 00:03:24.639
It'll break it down into different time parts and it looks really great in a table.

00:03:25.119 --> 00:03:30.000
And because we have these formatting functions in vector formatters now, this

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:32.800
also exists as vector format duration.

00:03:33.160 --> 00:03:37.199
In feature six, we have an upgraded GT safe and it uses webshot2.

00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:38.080
It's a better webshot.

00:03:38.119 --> 00:03:39.839
It's a sequel to the webshot package.

00:03:40.360 --> 00:03:43.720
And the main thing to know there is that it doesn't use phantom JS.

00:03:43.759 --> 00:03:48.160
It uses chromote and chromote is the thing that will take the screenshot of the table.

00:03:48.839 --> 00:03:53.679
And because of all this, you get better PNG snapshots of your table and you'll

00:03:53.679 --> 00:03:58.399
just generally have a better experience because before, well, it wasn't so good.

00:03:58.399 --> 00:04:02.080
You'd have weird things like, well, it was blurry for one thing.

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:07.320
And also certain things like bold text did not work at all, which was quite

00:04:07.320 --> 00:04:08.839
annoying for a lot of people I can imagine.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:10.199
But now this fixes it.

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:14.000
New GT safe in 0.7, it just does the trick.

00:04:14.479 --> 00:04:17.320
In feature seven, we have accessibility improvements for screen readers.

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:20.679
So if you use a screen reader, you'll find that tables are read more

00:04:20.679 --> 00:04:22.399
accurately, especially complex tables.

00:04:23.480 --> 00:04:25.640
So that's what's in 0.7 of GT.

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:29.279
Check out the blog posts on rstudio.com and also check out the new

00:04:29.279 --> 00:04:32.279
Twitter account at GT underscore package.

